Part A. Data Collection [5pt]¶

So far, we have worked with data sets that have been collected, cleaned, and curated by machine learning researchers and practitioners. Datasets like MNIST and CIFAR are often used as toy examples, both by students and by researchers testing new machine learning models.

In the real world, getting a clean data set is never that easy. More than half the work in applying machine learning is finding, gathering, cleaning, and formatting your data set.

The purpose of this assignment is to help you gain experience gathering your own data set, and understand the challenges involved in the data cleaning process.

American Sign Language¶

American Sign Language (ASL) is a complete, complex language that employs signs made by moving the hands combined with facial expressions and postures of the body. It is the primary language of many North Americans who are deaf and is one of several communication options used by people who are deaf or hard-of-hearing.

The hand gestures representing English alphabet are shown below. This assignment focuses on classifying a subset of these hand gesture images using convolutional neural networks. Specifically, given an image of a hand showing one of the letters A-I, we want to detect which letter is being represented.

Generating Data¶

We will produce the images required to assess our models by ourselves. You are required to collect, clean and submit three images each of Americal Sign Language gestures for letters A - I (total of 27 images) Steps involved in data collection

  1. Familiarize yourself with American Sign Language gestures for letters from A - I (9 letters).
  2. Take three pictures at slightly different orientation for each letter gesture using your mobile phone.
    • Ensure adequate lighting while you are capturing the images.
    • Use a white wall as your background.
    • Use your right hand to create gestures (for consistency).
    • Keep your right hand fairly apart from your body and any other obstructions.
    • Avoid having shadows on parts of your hand.
  3. Transfer the images to your laptop for cleaning.

Cleaning Data¶

To simplify the machine learning the task, we will standardize the training images. We will make sure that all our images are of the same size (224 x 224 pixels RGB), and have the hand in the center of the cropped regions.

You may use the following applications to crop and resize your images:

Mac

  • Use Preview: – Holding down CMD + Shift will keep a square aspect ratio while selecting the hand area. – Resize to 224x224 pixels.

Windows 10

  • Use Photos app to edit and crop the image and keep the aspect ratio a square.
  • Use Paint to resize the image to the final image size of 224x224 pixels.

Linux

  • You can use GIMP, imagemagick, or other tools of your choosing. You may also use online tools such as http://picresize.com All the above steps are illustrative only. You need not follow these steps but following these will ensure that you produce a good quality dataset. You will be judged based on the quality of the images alone. Please do not edit your photos in any other way. You should not need to change the aspect ratio of your image. You also should not digitally remove the background or shadows—instead, take photos with a white background and minimal shadows.

Accepted Images¶

Images will be accepted and graded based on the criteria below

  1. The final image should be size 224x224 pixels (RGB).
  2. The file format should be a .jpg file.
  3. The hand should be approximately centered on the frame.
  4. The hand should not be obscured or cut off.
  5. The photos follows the ASL gestures posted earlier.
  6. The photos were not edited in any other way (e.g. no electronic removal of shadows or background).

# Function to display a grid of images with labels
def show_images_grid(images, labels, class_names, rows=4, cols=8, figsize=(12, 8)):
    """
    Display a grid of images with their corresponding labels.

    Parameters:
    - images: List of images to be displayed.
    - labels: List of labels corresponding to the images.
    - class_names: List of class names for mapping label indices to class names.
    - rows: Number of rows in the grid (default is 4).
    - cols: Number of columns in the grid (default is 8).
    - figsize: Size of the figure (default is (12, 8)).

    Returns:
    - None: Displays the grid of images and labels.
    """

    # Create a subplot grid with specified number of rows and columns
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=figsize)
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)  # Adjust spacing between subplots

    # Iterate through rows and columns to display images with labels
    for i in range(rows):
        for j in range(cols):
            idx = i * cols + j  # Calculate index for accessing images and labels
            img = np.transpose(images[idx], [1, 2, 0])  # Transpose image dimensions for display
            axes[i, j].imshow(img)  # Display the image
            axes[i, j].set_title(class_names[labels[idx]])  # Set the title with the corresponding class name
            axes[i, j].axis('off')  # Turn off axis ticks and labels

def get_model_name(name, batch_size, learning_rate, epoch,ln):
    """ Generate a name for the model consisting of all the hyperparameter values

    Args:
        config: Configuration object containing the hyperparameters
    Returns:
        path: A string with the hyperparameter name and value concatenated
    """
    path = "model_{0}_bs{1}_lr{2}_epoch{3}_ln{4}".format(name,
                                                   batch_size,
                                                   learning_rate,
                                                   epoch,ln)
    return path

# Function to calculate error
def calculate_error(outputs, labels):
    _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
    correct = (predicted == labels).sum().item()
    error = 1 - correct / labels.size(0)
    return error

def plot_training_curve(path):
    """ Plots the training curve for a model run, given the csv files
    containing the train/validation error/loss.

    Args:
        path: The base path of the csv files produced during training
    """
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    train_err = np.loadtxt("{}_train_err.csv".format(path))
    val_err = np.loadtxt("{}_val_err.csv".format(path))
    train_loss = np.loadtxt("{}_train_loss.csv".format(path))
    val_loss = np.loadtxt("{}_val_loss.csv".format(path))
    plt.title("Train vs Validation Error")
    n = len(train_err) # number of epochs
    plt.plot(range(1,n+1), train_err, label="Train")
    plt.plot(range(1,n+1), val_err, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel("Error")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()
    plt.title("Train vs Validation Loss")
    plt.plot(range(1,n+1), train_loss, label="Train")
    plt.plot(range(1,n+1), val_loss, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

def get_accuracy(model, loader, criterion):
    """ A function that evaluates the performance of the model on the validation set.

     Args:
         model: PyTorch NN object
         loader: PyTorch data loader for the validation set
         criterion: The selected loss function

     Returns:
         err: A scalar for the avg classification error over the validation set
         loss: A scalar for the average loss function over the validation set
    """

    total_loss = 0
    total_err = 0
    total_epoch = 0

    for i, data in enumerate(loader, 0):
        imgs, labels = data

        outputs = (model(imgs))
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        corr = sum(torch.argmax(outputs, dim=1) != labels)
        total_err += int(corr)
        total_loss += loss.item()
        total_epoch += len(labels)

    err = float(total_err) / total_epoch
    loss = float(total_loss) / (i + 1)
    return err, loss

from zipfile import ZipFile

# Specify the path to the ZIP file containing the dataset
file_name = '/content/A2_Hand_Gesture_Dataset.zip'

# Use the 'with' statement to open the ZIP file in read mode ('r')
with ZipFile(file_name, 'r') as zip:
    # Extract all contents of the ZIP file into the current working directory
    zip.extractall()

    # Print a message indicating that the extraction process is complete
    print('Done')


# Specify the path to the dataset
dataset_path = '/content/Lab_3b_Gesture_Dataset'

# Specify the output directories for train, validation, and test sets
train_dir = '/content/training'
val_dir = '/content/validation'
test_dir = '/content/test'

# Create directories if they don't exist
os.makedirs(train_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(val_dir, exist_ok=True)
os.makedirs(test_dir, exist_ok=True)

# Dictionary to store counts for each class
class_counts = {}

# Iterate through each letter folder (A to I)
for letter in os.listdir(dataset_path):
    letter_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, letter)

    # Get a list of image filenames in the current letter folder
    images = [img for img in os.listdir(letter_path)]

    # Calculate the number of images for each split
    num_images = len(images)
    num_train = int(0.7 * num_images) # 70% for training
    num_val = int(0.20 * num_images)  # 20% for validation

    # Create directories for each letter in the train, validation, and test sets
    os.makedirs(os.path.join(train_dir, letter), exist_ok=True)
    os.makedirs(os.path.join(val_dir, letter), exist_ok=True)
    os.makedirs(os.path.join(test_dir, letter), exist_ok=True)

    # Split the images into train, validation, and test sets
    train_images = images[:num_train]
    val_images = images[num_train:num_train + num_val]
    test_images = images[num_train + num_val:] # 10% for testing

    # Move the images to the respective directories
    for img in train_images:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(letter_path, img),
                    os.path.join(train_dir, letter, img))

    for img in val_images:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(letter_path, img),
                    os.path.join(val_dir, letter, img))

    for img in test_images:
        shutil.move(os.path.join(letter_path, img),
                    os.path.join(test_dir, letter, img))

    # Store counts in the dictionary
    class_counts[letter] = {
        'total_images': num_images,
        'train': len(train_images),
        'validation': len(val_images),
        'test': len(test_images)
    }

print('Data split and organized into training, validation, and test sets.')

# Print the counts for each class
for letter, counts in class_counts.items():
    print(f"Letter: {letter}, Total Images: {counts['total_images']},Train: {counts['train']}, Validation: {counts['validation']}, Test: {counts['test']}")


# Calculate and display the total number of training, validation, and test images
total_train_images = sum(counts['train'] for counts in class_counts.values())
total_val_images = sum(counts['validation'] for counts in class_counts.values())
total_test_images = sum(counts['test'] for counts in class_counts.values())

print(f"\nTotal Training Images: {total_train_images}")
print(f"Total Validation Images: {total_val_images}")
print(f"Total Test Images: {total_test_images}")

class GestureCNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, Ln=64, num_classes=9):
        # Call the constructor of the parent class
        super(GestureCNN, self).__init__()

        # Name of the model
        self.name = "Gesture"

        # First convolutional layer: Takes 3 input channels,
        # produces 16 output channels, kernel size 5x5
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 16, kernel_size=5)

        # Second convolutional layer: Takes 16 input channels,
        # produces 32 output channels, kernel size 3x3
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=3)

        # Third convolutional layer: Takes 32 input channels,
        # produces 64 output channels, kernel size 3x3
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=3)

        # Max pooling layer: Reduces the spatial dimensions by a factor of 2
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)

        # First fully connected layer: Takes flattened
        # input (64 * 26 * 26), produces Ln output units
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(64 * 26 * 26, Ln)

        # Second fully connected layer (output layer):
        # Takes Ln input units, produces num_classes output units
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(Ln, num_classes)

    # The forward method is responsible for defining the forward pass of the network
    def forward(self, x):
        # First convolutional layer with max pooling and ReLU activation
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv1(x)))

        # Second convolutional layer with max pooling and ReLU activation
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv2(x)))

        # Third convolutional layer with max pooling and ReLU activation
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))

        # Flatten the output for the fully connected layers
        x = x.view(-1, 64 * 26 * 26)

        # First fully connected layer with ReLU activation
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))

        # Second fully connected layer (output layer)
        x = self.fc2(x)

        return x

'''
PROVIDE YOUR ANSWER BELOW

Abdullah: Replying to

"Explain your choice of neural network architecture: how many layers did you
choose? What types of layers did you use? Were they fully-connected or
convolutional? What about other decisions like pooling layers, activation
functions, number of channels / hidden units?"

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The chosen neural network architecture is designed for a hand gesture
classification task. The inspiration for the model was taken from the
pre-assignment codes and lecture slides:

Input Layer:
The input layer expects images with dimensions 224x224 and
three color channels (RGB).

Convolutional Layers:
Three convolutional layers (conv1, conv2, conv3) are used to
capture hierarchical features in the input images.
conv1 uses a 5x5 kernel size, followed by max pooling.
conv2 uses a 3x3 kernel size, followed by max pooling.
conv3 uses a 3x3 kernel size, followed by max pooling.

The number of output channels progressively increases (16, 32, 64),
allowing the network to learn more complex and abstract features.

Pooling Layers:
Max pooling layers follow each convolutional layer
to perform dimensionality reduction and provide translation invariance.

Pooling is performed with a 2x2 kernel and a stride of 2.

Activation Functions:
ReLU activation functions are applied after each convolutional layer.
ReLU introduces non-linearity to the model, helping it learn
complex mappings from inputs to outputs.

Flatten Layer:
Before the fully connected layers, a flatten operation is performed to
convert the 3D tensor to a 1D tensor, preparing it for the fully connected layers.

Fully Connected Layers:
Two fully connected layers (fc1, fc2) are included in the architecture.
The first fully connected layer (fc1) takes the flattened input and
produces Ln output units with a ReLU activation function.
The second fully connected layer (fc2) serves as the output layer,
taking Ln input units and producing num_classes output units.

Output Layer:
The model uses a linear activation in the output layer,
suitable for classification tasks, with as many units as there
are classes (A - I).

Number of Hidden Units:
The number of channels in convolutional layers and hidden units in the
fully connected layers (fc1 and fc2) was determined based on the
calculated dimensions.

The chosen architecture aims to capture relevant features from the input
images through convolutional and pooling operations, followed by classification
through fully connected layers. It strikes a balance between complexity and
simplicity, considering the task's requirements and the size of the dataset.
The use of multiple convolutional layers helps the model learn hierarchical
features, and max pooling aids in reducing spatial dimensions. The ReLU
activation functions introduce non-linearity, enhancing the model's capacity
to learn complex patterns in the data.

def train_model(model, num_epochs, learning_rate, batch_size,ln):

    # Define the paths to the train, validation, and test sets
    train_dir = '/content/training'
    val_dir = '/content/validation'
    test_dir = '/content/test'

    # Define transformations for the images
    transform = transforms.Compose([
        transforms.Resize((224, 224)),  # Resize images to a consistent size
        transforms.ToTensor(),  # Converts images to PyTorch tensors
    ])

    # Create datasets
    train_dataset = datasets.ImageFolder(root=train_dir, transform=transform)
    val_dataset = datasets.ImageFolder(root=val_dir, transform=transform)
    test_dataset = datasets.ImageFolder(root=test_dir, transform=transform)

    # Create data loaders
    train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
    val_loader = DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
    test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)

    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, momentum=0.9)

    train_err = []
    train_loss = []
    val_err = []
    val_loss = []

    # Function to calculate error
    def calculate_error(outputs, labels):
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        correct = (predicted == labels).sum().item()
        error = 1 - correct / labels.size(0)
        return error

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        running_loss = 0.0
        running_error = 0.0

        for inputs, labels in train_loader:
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            running_loss += loss.item()
            running_error += calculate_error(outputs, labels)

        # Calculate training error and loss
        train_err.append(running_error / len(train_loader))
        train_loss.append(running_loss / len(train_loader))

        print(f'Epoch {epoch + 1}/{num_epochs}, Loss: {train_loss[-1]}, Train Error: {train_err[-1]}')

        # Validation
        model.eval()
        val_loss_epoch = 0.0
        correct = 0
        total = 0

        with torch.no_grad():
            for inputs, labels in val_loader:
                outputs = model(inputs)
                loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
                val_loss_epoch += loss.item()

                _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
                total += labels.size(0)
                correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

            # Calculate validation error and loss
            val_err.append(1 - correct / total)
            val_loss.append(val_loss_epoch / len(val_loader))

            print(f'Validation Loss: {val_loss[-1]}, Validation Error: {val_err[-1]}')

        model_path = get_model_name(model.name, batch_size, learning_rate, epoch,ln)
        torch.save(model.state_dict(), model_path)

    # Save metrics to CSV files
    np.savetxt("{}_train_err.csv".format(model_path), train_err)
    np.savetxt("{}_train_loss.csv".format(model_path), train_loss)
    np.savetxt("{}_val_err.csv".format(model_path), val_err)
    np.savetxt("{}_val_loss.csv".format(model_path), val_loss)

# Unzip the dataset
file_name = '/content/Rasul-Abdullah_1011328243.zip'
with ZipFile(file_name, 'r') as zip:
    zip.extractall()
    print('Dataset extracted successfully.')

# Define the paths to the dataset
dataset_path = '/content/Rasul-Abdullah_1011328243'

# Define transformations for the images
transform = transforms.Compose([
    transforms.Resize((224, 224)),
    transforms.ToTensor(),
])

# Create the dataset
full_dataset = datasets.ImageFolder(root=dataset_path, transform=transform)

# Define the indices for training and validation sets
total_samples = len(full_dataset)
train_size = int(0.75 * total_samples)
val_size = total_samples - train_size

indices = list(range(total_samples))
train_indices, val_indices = indices[:train_size], indices[train_size:]

# Create DataLoader for training and validation sets
train_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(train_indices)
val_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(val_indices)

train_loader = DataLoader(full_dataset,sampler=train_sampler, shuffle=False)
val_loader = DataLoader(full_dataset, sampler=val_sampler, shuffle=False)
# Initialize the model
model = GestureCNN(Ln = 128)

# Set hyperparameters
num_epochs = 40
learning_rate = 0.002

# Define loss function and optimizer
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, momentum=0.9)

# Training loop
train_losses = []
val_losses = []
train_errors = []
val_errors = []

train_acc = []
val_acc = []

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    # Training
    model.train()
    train_loss = 0.0
    correct_train = 0
    total_train = 0
    for inputs, labels in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(inputs)
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        train_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)

        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        total_train += labels.size(0)
        correct_train += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

    train_accuracy = correct_train / total_train
    train_losses.append(train_loss / len(train_loader.dataset))
    train_errors.append(1 - train_accuracy)
    train_acc.append(train_accuracy)


    # Validation
    model.eval()
    val_loss = 0.0
    correct_val = 0
    total_val = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for inputs, labels in val_loader:
            outputs = model(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            val_loss += loss.item() * inputs.size(0)

            _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
            total_val += labels.size(0)
            correct_val += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

    val_accuracy = correct_val / total_val
    val_losses.append(val_loss / len(val_loader.dataset))
    val_errors.append(1 - val_accuracy)
    val_acc.append(val_accuracy)

    print(f'Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs}, Train Loss: {train_losses[-1]:.4f}, Val Loss: {val_losses[-1]:.4f}, Train Error: {train_errors[-1]:.4f}, Val Error: {val_errors[-1]:.4f}')

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

'''

------------------------------------------------------------------------

Learning Rate (lr):
The learning rate is a crucial hyperparameter that controls the step size
during the optimization process. A too high learning rate might cause the
model to converge too quickly or even overshoot the optimal weights, while a
too low learning rate might result in slow convergence or getting stuck in
local minima.

Batch Size:
Batch size determines the number of samples used in each iteration of the
training. A smaller batch size may result in a more stochastic gradient descent
and can help the model generalize better, while a larger batch size may lead to
faster convergence but might cause the model to
converge to a suboptimalsolution.

Number of Nodes in the Fully Connected Layers:
The architecture of the fully connected layers, including the number of
nodes in each layer, significantly impacts the model's capacity to learn
complex patterns and represent higher-level abstractions. Adjusting the
number of nodes in these layers can influence the model's ability to capture
and generalize from the learned features.

Part 4. Transfer Learning [8pt]¶

For many image classification tasks, it is generally not a good idea to train a very large deep neural network model from scratch due to the enormous compute requirements and lack of sufficient amounts of training data.

One of the better options is to try using an existing model that performs a similar task to the one you need to solve. This method of utilizing a pre-trained network for other similar tasks is broadly termed Transfer Learning. In this assignment, we will use Transfer Learning to extract features from the hand gesture images. Then, train a smaller network to use these features as input and classify the hand gestures.

As you have learned from the CNN lecture, convolution layers extract various features from the images which get utilized by the fully connected layers for correct classification. AlexNet architecture played a pivotal role in establishing Deep Neural Nets as a go-to tool for image classification problems and we will use an ImageNet pre-trained AlexNet model to extract features in this assignment.

In [18]:
########################## HELPER FUNCTIONS FOR TRANSFER LEARNING

# Define dataloader parameters
batch_size = 32
num_workers = 0

# Prepare data loaders
train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size,
                                           num_workers=num_workers, shuffle=True)
val_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(val_dataset, batch_size=batch_size,
                                         num_workers=num_workers, shuffle=True)

def get_accuracy_alex(model, data_loader):

    total_loss = 0
    total_err = 0
    total_epoch = 0
    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    model.eval()

    for imgs, labels in data_loader:

        imgs = alexnet.features(imgs)

        outputs = (model(imgs))
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        corr = sum(torch.argmax(outputs, dim=1) != labels)
        total_err += int(corr)
        total_loss += loss.item()
        total_epoch += len(labels)

    err = float(total_err) / total_epoch
    loss = float(total_loss) / total_epoch
    return err, loss

The alexnet model is split up into two components: alexnet.features and alexnet.classifier. The first neural network component, alexnet.features, is used to compute convolutional features, which are taken as input in alexnet.classifier.

The neural network alexnet.features expects an image tensor of shape Nx3x224x224 as input and it will output a tensor of shape Nx256x6x6 . (N = batch size).

# TO BE COMPLETED


# Function to get AlexNet features
def get_alexnet_features(model, data_loader):
    model.eval()
    all_features = []

    with torch.no_grad():
        for imgs, labels in data_loader:
            features = model.features(imgs)
            all_features.append(features)

    return torch.cat(all_features, dim=0)

# Compute AlexNet features for training data
train_features = get_alexnet_features(alexnet, train_loader)

# Compute AlexNet features for validation data
val_features = get_alexnet_features(alexnet, val_loader)

# Assuming you have a test_loader for your test data
# Compute AlexNet features for test data
test_features = get_alexnet_features(alexnet, test_loader)

# Save the computed features to files
torch.save(train_features, 'train_features.pth')
torch.save(val_features, 'val_features.pth')
torch.save(test_features, 'test_features.pth')

class CustomClassifier(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        """
        Constructor for the CustomClassifier class.

        This neural network consists of three fully connected (linear) layers.
        The first layer has 256*6*6 input features, the second layer
        has 4500 hidden units, and the third layer has 9 output units.

        Activation functions (ReLU) are applied after the first two layers.
        """
        super(CustomClassifier, self).__init__()

        # First fully connected layer
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(256*6*6, 4500)

        # Second fully connected layer
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(4500, 4500)

        # Third fully connected layer (output layer)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(4500, 9)

    def forward(self, x):
        """
        Forward method that defines the forward pass of the neural network.

        Applies the linear transformations defined in the
        constructor along with ReLU activations.

        Parameters:
        - x: Input tensor of shape (batch_size, 256*6*6)

        Returns:
        - Output tensor of shape (batch_size, 9)
        """
        x = x.view(-1, 256*6*6)  # Flatten the input tensor
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))  # ReLU activation first fully connected layer
        x = F.relu(self.fc2(x))  # ReLU activation second fully connected layer
        x = self.fc3(x)          # Output layer without activation function
        return x

'''
PROVIDE YOUR ANSWER BELOW
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Considering the context of transfer learning using AlexNet features,
the choice of the neural network architecture involves building upon the
features extracted by AlexNet.

AlexNet Features:
The initial layers of AlexNet consist of convolutional layers that are
effective at capturing hierarchical features from images.

These features, obtained from the AlexNet model,
serve as the input to the custom classifier.

Custom Classifier Architecture:
Linear Layers: The custom classifier consists of three fully connected
(linear) layers (fc1, fc2, and fc3).

Activation Function: Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU) activation functions are
applied after the first two fully connected layers to introduce non-linearity.

Choice of Layers:
The decision to use only linear layers in the custom classifier is based on
the fact that the features obtained from AlexNet already represent high-level
abstractions, and additional convolutional layers may not provide
significant benefits in this context.

Including convolutional layers in this case is optional and would depend on
the specific characteristics of the dataset and the desired level of
abstraction in the custom classifier.

Pooling Layers:
Since AlexNet already incorporates pooling layers in its architecture,
additional pooling layers are not explicitly added to the custom classifier.

Number of Hidden Units:
The first fully connected layer (fc1) has 4500 hidden units, and the second
fully connected layer (fc2) also has 4500 hidden units.
The output layer (fc3) has 9 units, corresponding to the number of classes
in the target classification task.

In conlcusion, the custom classifier extends the features extracted by AlexNet
with fully connected layers and ReLU activations, leveraging the hierarchical
representations learned by the convolutional layers of AlexNet.
This architecture balances the complexity of the model while utilizing
the transfer learning benefits of the pre-trained AlexNet.

def train(model, train_loader, val_loader, num_epochs):
    criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
    optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01, momentum=0.9)

    train_losses, train_acc, val_acc, val_loss = [], [], [], []

    # Training loop
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        epoch_loss = 0.0
        correct_train = 0
        total_train = 0

        for imgs, labels in train_loader:
            imgs = alexnet.features(imgs)

            out = model(imgs)
            loss = criterion(out, labels)

            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

            # Save the current training information
            epoch_loss += loss.item() / batch_size  # Adjusted for batch size

            pred_train = out.max(1, keepdim=True)[1]
            correct_train += pred_train.eq(labels.view_as(pred_train)).sum().item()
            total_train += imgs.shape[0]

        train_accuracy = correct_train / total_train
        epoch_loss /= len(train_loader.dataset)
        val_err, vl = get_accuracy_alex(model, val_loader)
        train_losses.append(epoch_loss)  # Append loss to losses at each iteration

        val_loss.append(vl)
        train_acc.append(train_accuracy)
        val_acc.append(1- val_err)

        # Print the training information after each epoch
        print(f'Epoch {epoch + 1}/{num_epochs}, Training Loss: {epoch_loss:.4f}, Validation Loss: {vl:.4f}, Training Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}, Validation Accuracy: {1- val_err:.4f}')

    # Plotting after the training loop
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), train_losses, label="Train")
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), val_loss, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.title("Training Loss Curve")

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), train_acc, label="Train")
    plt.plot(range(1, num_epochs + 1), val_acc, label="Validation")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.title("Training and Validation Accuracy Curve")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.show()

    print("Final Training Accuracy: {}".format(train_acc[-1]))
    print("Final Validation Accuracy: {}".format(val_acc[-1]))


model = CustomClassifier()


# Train the model
train(model, train_loader, val_loader, num_epochs=8)
